"Seneviratne S.I., Lüthi D., Litschi M., Schär C.","Land-atmosphere coupling and climate change in Europe",2006,"Nature","443","7108",,"205","209",,,10.1038/nature05095,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33748660216&partnerID=40&md5=5edad97bf16e32ddd97beb90de8edaa2","Institute for Atmospheric and Climate Science, ETH Zurich, Universitätsstrasse 16, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland","Seneviratne, S.I., Institute for Atmospheric and Climate Science, ETH Zurich, Universitätsstrasse 16, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland; Lüthi, D., Institute for Atmospheric and Climate Science, ETH Zurich, Universitätsstrasse 16, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland; Litschi, M., Institute for Atmospheric and Climate Science, ETH Zurich, Universitätsstrasse 16, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland; Schär, C., Institute for Atmospheric and Climate Science, ETH Zurich, Universitätsstrasse 16, 8092 Zurich, Switzerland","Increasing greenhouse gas concentrations are expected to enhance the interannual variability of summer climate in Europe and other mid-latitude regions, potentially causing more frequent heatwaves. Climate models consistently predict an increase in the variability of summer temperatures in these areas, but the underlying mechanisms responsible for this increase remain uncertain. Here we explore these mechanisms using regional simulations of recent and future climatic conditions with and without land-atmosphere interactions. Our results indicate that the increase in summer temperature variability predicted in central and eastern Europe is mainly due to feedbacks between the land surface and the atmosphere. Furthermore, they suggest that land-atmosphere interactions increase climate variability in this region because climatic regimes in Europe shift northwards in response to increasing greenhouse gas concentrations, creating a new transitional climate zone with strong land-atmosphere coupling in central and eastern Europe. These findings emphasize the importance of soil-moisture-temperature feedbacks (in addition to soil-moisture-precipitation feedbacks) in influencing summer climate variability and the potential migration of climate zones with strong land-atmosphere coupling as a consequence of global warming. This highlights the crucial role of land-atmosphere interactions in future climate change. © 2006 Nature Publishing Group.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Feedback; Geographical regions; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Waves; Climatic conditions; Greenhouse gas interactions; Heatwaves; Land-atmosphere interactions; Climate change; air-soil interaction; annual variation; atmospheric structure; climate change; climate conditions; global warming; greenhouse gas; heat transfer; summer; temperature effect; article; atmosphere; climate; climate change; Europe; greenhouse effect; land biome; priority journal; summer; temperature measurement; Eurasia; Europe",,,,,,"Schär, C., The role of increasing temperature variability in European summer heatwaves (2004) Nature, 427, pp. 332-336; Giorgi, F., Bi, X., Pal, J.S., Mean, interannual variability and trends in a regional climate change experiment over Europe. II. Climate change scenarios (1971-2100) (2004) Clim. Dyn., 23, pp. 839-858; Vidale, P.L., Lüthi, D., Wegmann, R., Schär, C., European climate variability in a heterogeneous multi-model ensemble Clim. Change, , in the press; Räisänen, J., CO2-induced changes in interannual temperature and precipitation variability in 19 CMIP2 experiments (2002) J. Clim., 15, pp. 2395-2411; Meehl, G.A., Tebaldi, C., More intense, more frequent, and longer lasting heat waves in the 21st century (2004) Science, 305, pp. 994-997; Lenderink, G., Van Ulden, A., Van Den Hurk, B., Van Meijgaard, E., Summertime interannual temperature variability in an ensemble of regional model simulations: Analysis of surface energy budget Clim. Change, , in the press; Koster, R.D., Regions of strong coupling between soil moisture and precipitation (2004) Science, 305, pp. 1138-1140; Betts, A.K., Unde